  "text": "The 458 SNP markers were able to discriminate between all the cowpea accessions studied. Previous could not discriminate all accessions, but the increase number of markers used here and their high levels of polymorphism allowed the discrimination of even closely related accessions such as BBE, M, B and ME (segregated lines of Gh4524). This confirms the robustness of SNP markers in diversity studies as reported by [CITATION_1] . The separation of the four Gh4524 lines on the other hand could most probably be due to segregation as [CITATION_2] were able to identify duplicates from the USDA' core cowpea collection with SNP markers.",
